<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-317-251  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 317 251.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic News  Feb 6 1989 v35 n1744 pS6(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>'Stealth' makers emerge from dark; stretch-outs, delays threatenavionics suppliers and others. (Special Report on MilitaryElectronics)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Robertson, Jack.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The Pentagon has lifted the veil of secrecy from its arsenal of'stealth' aircraft and missiles.andP;  Although the budget funding forthe stealth weapons is still classified, it is known that reportedstretch-outs and delays on many of the projects have negativelyimpacted select avionic suppliers such as IBM, Hughes and Unisys,just as severely as it has the airframe prime contractors.andP;  TheAir Force has conceded that Northrop's B-2 Stealth Bomber isalready a year behind schedule and is being threatened by furtherCongressional funding cuts in 1989.andP;  Many of the avionicsubcontractors are hoping the controversial cost hikes anddevelopment problems now coming to light have been overcome,fearing that the number of aircraft and missiles to be procuredwill be decreased leading to fewer subsystem sales.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     BudgetingMilitaryDefense ContractsWeapons.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>